\#\#\# Top Answer: There are a couple of things that are wrong with your code above. As pointed out, having multiple return statement will not work. Also, when defining a new object, it is preferable to use the object literal syntax over using `new Object`.

What you would normally do is something more like this:

```
var function_to_test = function () {
  var person = {
    name : "Nicholas",
    age : 29
  };

  return person;
};

```

Using the function above, there are a couple of ways you could test this. One it to mock out the console.log object using [Jasmine Spies](https://jasmine.github.io/api/edge/Spy).

```
it("should test for the function_to_test's console output", function () {
    console.log = jasmine.createSpy("log");
    var person = function_to_test();
    expect(console.log).toHaveBeenCalledWith(person);
});

```

The other is to test the actual output of the function.

```
it("should return a person", function () {
    var person = function_to_test();
    expect(person).toEqual({ name : "Nicholas", age : 29 });
